Sunday, December 28, 2025

How To Build Something that Matters

There's a particular feeling I get when I sit down with a frontier model and an idea that won't leave me alone.

It's not the feeling of having a tool. It's the feeling of having a thinking partner who doesn't get tired, doesn't get defensive, and doesn't need coffee breaks. A partner who can hold the entire context of what I'm building while I explore the edges of what's possible.

I've built over 160 projects in the last eighteen months. I've taught thousands of students how to think about emerging technology. I've written books about disruption and transformation. And here's what I've learned: the gap between understanding something and building something is where all the real insight lives.

Most people consume AI. They prompt, they receive, they move on. But there's another way. A way that treats every session with a frontier model as a collaboration on something that didn't exist before. Not content. Not summaries. Systems. Products. Things that work.

How does it work? How do you build something that matters?

It starts with a simple belief: every project is a hypothesis about how technology can create value. The only way to test a hypothesis is to ship it. The only way to learn is to build. The only way to know if something matters is to release it into the world and see if it survives contact with reality.

The Phase Change

Something happened in the last eighteen months.

And honestly, I didn't fully understand why until I saw Andrej Karpathy, one of the architects of modern AI, say something that stopped me cold:

https://x.com/karpathy/status/2004607146781278521

He said he feels behind.

Not confused. Not skeptical. Behind.

Think about that for a second. The guy who helped build GPT. The former head of AI at Tesla. Looking at what's possible now and thinking: I'm not moving fast enough.

That's not imposter syndrome. That's a signal.

Here's the thing most people miss: programming didn't get faster. It changed shape.

For decades, progress meant writing denser code. More logic. More precision. More control. You proved your skill by how much complexity you could wrangle into working software.

Now the opposite is happening.

Human input is getting sparser. Machine output is getting wildly larger. You don't write the system anymore. You orchestrate it.

Prompts instead of functions. Agents instead of modules. Verification instead of execution.

And that shift breaks old instincts.

The bottleneck moved. It used to be: can you write correct instructions? Now it's: can you clearly state intent and reliably judge whether reality matches it?

Generation is cheap. Judgment is scarce.

That's the uncomfortable part. The tools are probabilistic. Outputs vary. Mistakes are confident. Failures are subtle. You're no longer debugging code. You're debugging behavior.

That's a very different muscle. And nobody gave us a manual.

Why This Feels Uncomfortable

This is exactly why smart people feel behind despite being excellent.

Not because they forgot how to build. But because their mental model expired.

The abstraction layer moved. And when abstractions move, experience briefly looks like friction.

I watch senior engineers struggle with this. They've spent years developing instincts for writing precise, deterministic code. Now they're working with systems that are probabilistic, fallible, and confidently wrong. Their hard-won intuitions suddenly work against them.

Meanwhile, I see people with less traditional experience building things that would have taken teams of engineers a year ago. Not because they're smarter. Because they're not fighting the new shape of the work.

The old question was: how do I implement this?

The new question is: how do I describe what I want clearly enough that an agent can implement it, and how do I know if it actually did?

That's not a small shift. That's a complete inversion of the skill stack.

The New Literacy

So what does it actually mean to build with agents?

It means you stop thinking of AI as a tool and start thinking of it as a collaborator with capabilities and limitations you need to understand deeply.

Here's what I've learned matters:

Expressing intent precisely. The clearer you can articulate what you want, the better the output. This sounds obvious but it's not. Most people are vague because they've never had to be precise. When you're writing code yourself, you can hold ambiguity in your head and resolve it as you go. When you're directing an agent, ambiguity becomes errors.

Constraining systems intelligently. Agents will do exactly what you ask, including the parts you didn't think through. The skill is knowing where to set boundaries. What should the system never do? What edge cases matter? What failures are acceptable and which are catastrophic?

Verifying outputs ruthlessly. Generation is cheap. That's the point. But cheap generation means you need to be the quality filter. You need to know what good looks like. You need to catch the confident mistakes. You need to test behavior, not just syntax.

Knowing when not to trust the machine. This might be the hardest one. Agents are convincing even when they're wrong. They don't hesitate. They don't signal uncertainty well. You have to develop your own sense of when to verify, when to push back, when to start over.

The people who win in this era won't be the ones who write the most code.

They'll be the ones who express intent precisely, constrain intelligently, verify ruthlessly, and know when the machine is wrong.

They won't look busy. They'll look calm.

Building to Learn

I have a philosophy I come back to constantly: build to learn, teach to share, ship to validate.

Every project is an experiment. Not a performance. Not a product launch. An experiment.

When I build something, I'm testing a hypothesis about what's possible. About what's useful. About what works. The only way to get real feedback is to ship it. To put it in front of reality and see what happens.

Most of what I build doesn't become a company. It becomes knowledge. It becomes intuition. It becomes the foundation for the next thing I build.

That's the real advantage of working with agents. The cost of experimentation collapsed. Ideas that would have taken weeks to test now take hours. Systems that would have required a team can be prototyped alone.

This changes how you think about risk. When building is cheap, you can afford to be wrong more often. You can afford to try the weird idea. You can afford to find out instead of arguing about it in a meeting.

The loop tightens. Hypothesis. Build. Ship. Learn. Repeat.

The Vibe of Building

There's a mode I slip into when this is working well. I call it vibe coding.

It's not about writing code carefully. It's about staying in flow while the system takes shape around you. You describe what you want. The agent builds it. You react. You refine. You keep moving.

The key is momentum. You don't stop to perfect things. You don't debate architecture for hours. You build something that works, then you make it better. Or you throw it away and try something else.

This only works if you trust yourself to judge the output. If you can look at what the agent built and know whether it's right. That judgment is the skill. The building itself is almost free now.

I've had days where I built three complete systems before dinner. Not toys. Working systems with databases and APIs and user interfaces. Things that would have taken weeks a few years ago.

It's not that I'm faster. It's that the nature of the work changed. I'm not typing anymore. I'm directing. I'm verifying. I'm deciding.

What Actually Matters

So what makes something matter?

I think about this a lot. With building this cheap, you can make almost anything. The question becomes: should you?

For me, something matters if it creates real value for real people. Not theoretical value. Not someday value. Value that someone would notice if it disappeared tomorrow.

It matters if it teaches me something I couldn't learn any other way. Every project should leave me knowing something I didn't know before.

It matters if it moves the conversation forward. If it shows people what's possible. If it opens up new questions worth asking.

And maybe most importantly, it matters if it survives contact with reality. If you ship it and it works. If people use it. If it holds up.

That's the test. Not how clever it is. Not how complex. Does it work? Does it matter to anyone besides you?

The Edge Belongs to the Learners

When the people who shaped the old world start feeling uneasy in the new one, it doesn't mean the future is broken.

It means the advantage has reset.

Right now, the edge belongs to those who stop trying to control intelligence and learn how to direct it.

The manual isn't coming. The abstraction layer already moved. The people who figure out how to work at this new level will build things the rest of the world thinks is impossible.

And the beautiful part? You don't need permission. You don't need credentials. You don't need a team or funding or a decade of experience.

You need a frontier model, a clear intent, and the willingness to ship something before you think it's ready.

Build to learn. Teach to share. Ship to validate.

That's how you build anything that matters.

2025 Victor del Rosal
